---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro'
import Header from '../components/Header.tsx'
import '../index.css'
---

<Layout title="About - PhyloGuessr">
  <div class="game">
    <Header client:load />
    <div class="about-page">
      <h2>About PhyloGuessr</h2>

      <h3>How it works</h3>
      <p>Pick which two of three organisms are most closely related — the pair sharing the most recent common ancestor.</p>

      <h3>Data sources</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Taxonomy from <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/taxonomy" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NCBI Taxonomy</a></li>
        <li>Images from <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Wikipedia</a></li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Contribute</h3>
      <p><a href="https://github.com/cmdcolin/phyloguessr" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GitHub</a> · <a href="https://github.com/cmdcolin/phyloguessr/issues" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Report bugs or suggest trios</a> · <a href="/donate">Donate</a></p>

      <h3>A note on NCBI Taxonomy</h3>
      <p>The NCBI Taxonomy database is a classification, not a true phylogeny. It is not a primary source for phylogenetic information, and does not follow a single taxonomic treatise — instead it incorporates knowledge from a variety of sources including published literature, web-based databases, and outside experts. As a result, the relationships it describes may not always reflect the latest phylogenetic understanding. See the <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK53759/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NCBI Taxonomy Help</a> for more details on how the database is curated.</p>


      <h3>Use of AI</h3>
      <p>Claude Code AI was used to help create this website including both code and various text on our easy mode aka surprisingFacts, but we tried to ensure correctness of the facts and code also. If you spot any errors please report them on <a href="https://github.com/cmdcolin/phyloguessr/issues" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GitHub</a> or email <a href="mailto:colin.diesh@gmail.com">colin.diesh@gmail.com</a>.</p>

      <h3>Why phylogeny and taxonomy matter</h3>
      <p>Phylogeny — the evolutionary relationships among species — underpins much of biology. Taxonomy provides the shared naming system that makes this work: it organizes life's diversity while phylogeny reveals the evolutionary history behind it.</p>

      <h4>Applied sciences</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Drug discovery — picking model organisms closest to humans</li>
        <li>Agriculture — finding wild relatives for crop breeding</li>
        <li>Epidemiology — tracking pathogen evolution and spread</li>
        <li>Antibiotic resistance — tracing resistance gene spread across bacteria</li>
        <li>Forensics — linking biological evidence to its source</li>
        <li>Conservation — prioritizing evolutionarily unique lineages</li>
        <li>Bioprospecting — finding useful compounds by screening relatives of known producers</li>
      </ul>

      <h4>Genomics and molecular biology</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Comparative genomics — predicting gene function from related species</li>
        <li>Ancestral reconstruction — inferring ancient proteins and traits</li>
        <li>Orthologs vs. paralogs — distinguishing speciation from duplication events</li>
        <li>Horizontal gene transfer — detecting genes that jumped between species</li>
        <li>Molecular clocks — dating when lineages diverged</li>
        <li>Metagenomics — classifying organisms in environmental DNA samples</li>
      </ul>

      <h4>Ecology and evolution</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Taxonomy — defining and naming species within an evolutionary framework</li>
        <li>Biogeography — explaining species distributions across the globe</li>
        <li>Community ecology — understanding how species assemblages form</li>
        <li>Coevolution — studying reciprocal adaptations between hosts and parasites</li>
        <li>Adaptive radiation — understanding how lineages rapidly diversify into new niches</li>
        <li>Trait evolution — reconstructing when traits like flight, venom, or photosynthesis arose or were lost</li>
        <li>Convergent evolution — identifying traits that evolved independently in unrelated lineages</li>
        <li>Phylogeography — tracing how populations spread and diverged across geography</li>
      </ul>
      <h3>FAQ</h3>

      <h4>Where did the idea come from?</h4>
      <p>I attended a Science on Tap trivia night long ago and they did this type of game live ith a powerpoint and it was very entertaining, and I thought it would make a fun web game.</p>

      <h4>Can I use this for my own trivia night or classroom?</h4>
      <p>Absolutely! Feel free to use the website or any of the data on it for trivia, teaching, or anything else.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
